{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.13,0.11,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92448"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/109"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75765"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2905"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41991"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92448"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with several months of worsening frustration, irritability, and low mood. He reports difficulties maintaining his grip on tools at his work as a mechanic, with increasing involuntary movements of his hands and arms. He is struggling to concentrate and maintain the apprentice roster at his garage. He has been experiencing uncharacteristic verbal outbursts. His mother abandoned her career as an artist due to involuntary spasms and died by suicide in her early 50s.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hepatic steatosis. His medications include a recently completed course of phenoxymethylpenicillin for streptococcal pharyngitis. He drinks 4-5 standard drinks per night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears restless and fidgety. His vital signs are within normal limits. He displays irregular, asymmetric, non-repetitive, jerky movements of his arms and occasionally cocks his head at random intervals. He often diverts these movements into gestures, smoothing his trousers, or running his hand through his hair.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Huntington disease","Sydenham chorea","Tourette syndrome","Wilson disease","Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive neurocognitive symptoms and involuntary movements suggestive of a neurodegenerative disease. The combination of chorea, cognitive decline, and psychiatric symptoms, along with the family history of similar symptoms and suicide in his mother, strongly suggests an inherited condition. This patient has presented with a constellation of chronic progressive neurocognitive symptoms and involuntary movements, which together suggest a neurodegenerative disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant condition characterised by the triad of progressive chorea (irregular, flowing, non-repetitive involuntary movements), cognitive decline (particularly executive function), and psychiatric symptoms (commonly irritability, depression, and impulsivity). The age of onset is typically 30-50 years, matching this patient\u0027s presentation. Given the autosomal dominant inheritance pattern, this patient has a 50% chance of having inherited the condition from his affected mother.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents before age 30 and while it can cause neuropsychiatric symptoms and liver disease, chorea is uncommon. Kayser-Fleischer rings would be expected on examination. The patient\u0027s liver abnormalities are more likely related to alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESydenham chorea\u003C/strong\u003E occurs following Group A streptococcal infection, but almost exclusively affects children and adolescents. While this patient has recently had streptococcal pharyngitis, his age and progressive course make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETourette syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves stereotyped, repetitive movements (tics) that can be temporarily suppressed and are preceded by an urge to perform the movement. It typically begins in childhood and would not explain the cognitive decline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreutzfeldt-Jakob disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes rapidly progressive dementia with myoclonus (sudden, shock-like movements) rather than chorea. The typical course is much more rapid than this patient\u0027s presentation, usually leading to death within one year of symptom onset.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Huntington disease is an autosomal dominant inherited disorder characterised by progressive chorea, cognitive decline, and psychiatric symptoms.","Chorea consists of brief, irregular, non-repetitive involuntary movements that flow randomly between body parts."],"references":["Stoker TB, Mason SL, Greenland JC, Holden ST, Santini H, Barker RA. Huntington\u0027s disease: diagnosis and management. Pract Neurol. 2022;22(1):32-41. doi:10.1136/practneurol-2021-003074","Termsarasab P. Chorea. Continuum (Minneap Minn). 2019 Aug;25(4):1001-1035.","Suchowersky O, Bouchard M. Overview of Chorea. UpToDate. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-chorea"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75765"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75765"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T20:17:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T20:17:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"109"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"descri